{"vocabInfos":[{"lsjDefs":"<b> χρῡσός</b>, ὁ, <br /> <b>gold,</b> τιμῆς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 18.475, etc.; coupled with other precious things, e.g. χαλκός, σίδηρος, 6.48 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; ἐσθής, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 5.38 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; χρυσὸν κέρασιν περιχεύας (of a victim) [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 10.294 = 8th c.BC: Odyssea Homerus Epicus “Odyssey” 3.384, compare 437; ὡς δ᾽ ὅτε τις χρυσὸν περιχεύεται ἀργύρῳ 6.232; χ. δαμασίφρων 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 13.78 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; κοῖλος ἄργυρος καὶ χ. silver and <b>gold</b> plate, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th c.BC: Theopompus Historicus 283a, compare 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Nav.” 20 \">Refs 4th c.BC+</a>]; λευκὸς χ. white <b>gold,</b> i.e. gold alloyed with silver, opposed to χ. ἄπεφθος refined <b>gold,</b> [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Herodotus Historicus 1.50; χ. ἑψόμενος 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 4.82; χρυσὸν καθαίρειν 5th-6th c.BC: Plato Philosophus “Politicus” 303d; βασανίζειν ἐν πυρί [prev. author] “R.” 413e. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__2</b></Level3> <b>gold,</b> to express anything made of gold, e. g. <b>golden</b> armour or raiment, χρυσὸν.. ἔδυνε περὶ χροΐ, of Zeus, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 8th c.BC: Ilias Homerus Epicus “Illiad” 8.43 \">Refs 8th c.BC+</a>]; of Poseidon, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 13.25; τὸ ἐμὸν σῶμα μήτε ἐν χ. θῆτε.. 5th-6th c.BC: Xenophon Historicus “Institutio Cyri (Cyropaedia)” 8.7.25 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]; ἀραρότως σύνδεσμα χρυσὸς (a gold crown) εἶχε [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Medea” 1193; ἐν χρυσῷ πίνειν 2nd c.AD: Lucianus Sophista “Merc. Cond.” 26. \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>]<br /><Level3><b>__3</b></Level3> frequently used by Poets to denote <b>anything dear</b> or <b>precious,</b> ταῦτα μὲν.. κρείσσονα χρυσοῦ.. φωνεῖς [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 4th-5th c.BC: Aeschylus Tragicus “Choephori” 372 (_anapaest meter_); ὁ χ. ἧσσον κτῆμα τοῦ κλάειν ἂν ἦν 5th c.BC: Sophocles Tragicus “Fragmenta” 557; ὡς χρυσὸς αὐτῷ τἀμὰ.. κακὰ δόξει ποτ᾽ εἶναι 5th c.BC: Euripides Tragicus “Troades” 432, compare 1st c.BC: Dionysius Halicarnassensis “Ars Rhetorica” 9.4; compare 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 1.1, 3.42, 1st-2nd c.AD: Plutarchus Biographus et Philosophus “Sertorius” 5: _metaphorically_ also, χρυσὸς ἐπῶν\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] <b>golden</b> words, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th-6th c.BC: Aristophanes Comicus “Plutus” 268; χρυσῷ πάττειν τινά [prev. author] “Nu.” 912 (_anapaest meter_); ὗσαι χρυσόν τινι 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “O.” 7.50. [ῡ] in χρυσός\">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>] and all derivations, though Lyric Poets sometimes made υ short in the <i>adjective</i> χρύσεος (which see); once we have χρῠσός, [<a href=\"javascript:void(0)\" title=\" 5th c.BC: Pindarus Lyricus “N.” 7.78 \">Refs 5th c.BC+</a>].] (Borrowed from Semitic, cf. Hebrew <b>chārūts,</b> Assyr. <i>h_urāšu</i> 'gold', Aramaic <i>hara</i> 'yellow'.)","strongNumber":"G5557","accentedUnicode":"χρυσός","relatedNos":[{"strongNumber":"G5552","matchingForm":"χρύσεος","stepTransliteration":"chruseos","gloss":"golden","_zh_tw_Gloss":"金","_es_Gloss":"de oro","_zh_Gloss":"金"},{"strongNumber":"G5553","matchingForm":"χρυσίον","stepTransliteration":"chrusion","gloss":"gold","_zh_tw_Gloss":"金","_es_Gloss":"oro","_zh_Gloss":"金"},{"strongNumber":"G5558","matchingForm":"χρυσόω","stepTransliteration":"chrusoō","gloss":"to gild","_zh_tw_Gloss":"為妝飾","_es_Gloss":"cubrir de oro","_zh_Gloss":"为妆饰"}],"shortDef":"gold","mediumDef":"<b>gold,</b> <ref='Mat.2.11; 23:16, 17'>Mt. 2:11; 23:16, 17</ref>; <i>metonymy</i> <b>gold ornaments,</b> <ref='1Ti.2.9'>1Tim. 2:9;</ref> <b>gold coin, money,</b> <ref='Mat.10.9'>Mt. 10:9</ref>","stepGloss":"gold","stepTransliteratio